Upon its release, ''A Different Kind of Truth'' received positive reviews from music critics.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whitman|first=Howard|title=CD Review <U+2014> Van Halen: A Different Kind of Truth|url=http://www.technologytell.com/hometech/83592/cd-review-van-halen-a-different-kind-of-truth/|work=Technology Tell|publisher=www.technologytell.com|accessdate=4/2/2012}}</ref><ref name="Metacritic">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/a-different-kind-of-truth |title=A Different Kind of Truth Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2010-09-28}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 73, based on 21 reviews, which is on the high end of "generally favorable reviews."<ref name="Metacritic"/> 

''[[The Montreal Gazette]]'' gave the album 4/5 stars, and ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the album 3.5/4 stars, and said that "this is the true kick in the butt that arena rock desperately needs."<ref name="usatoday1"/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the album four stars out of a possible five, writing that the album was "a frequently thrilling return" with songs that "crackle, fizz, and bulge with priapic exuberance".<ref name=guardian/> Likewise, [[Allmusic]] writer Stephen Thomas Erlewine rated the album four stars out of five and wrote: "Van Halen are using their history to revive their present and they succeed surprisingly well on ''A Different Kind of Truth''."<ref name="AM"/> William Clark of Guitar International gave the album a positive review, saying "''A Different Kind of Truth'' features some of the most elaborate, expansive, and simply wowing guitar playing that Eddie has passionately poured into a single album".<ref name="GuitarInternational.com">{{cite web | work=http://guitarinternational.com/2012/09/20/review-van-halens-a-different-kind-of-truth-cd-and-tab-book/| title=Review: Van Halen's A Different Kind of Truth CD and Tab Book | accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref>

''[[SPIN magazine]]'' wrote, "the frantic, haute-for-teacher "As Is" and the mid-tempo shoulda-been-the-single "You and Your Blues" can hang with any heavy-breathing romp they made in their heyday."<ref name="autogenerated1"/> [[The A.V. Club]]'s Steven Hyden stated, "After so many years of fumbling dysfunction that reduced the once-proud Van Halen name to a laughingstock, ''A Different Kind Of Truth'' matters because it<U+2019>s a reminder of why this band mattered," while noting that, "Roth deserves some of the credit for that. For whatever reason, when Roth is in the band, Eddie Van Halen plays guitar like the world wants him to play guitar."<ref name=avclub/> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the album 3.5 out of 5 stars, with critic Rob Sheffield stating, "Van Halen's "heard you missed us, we're back" album is not only the most long-awaited reunion joint in the history of reunion joints, it is <U+2013> against all reasonable expectations <U+2013> a real Van Halen album."<ref name="RS1"/>

''[[Guitar World]]'' picked ''A Different Kind of Truth'' as the best album of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/guitar-worlds-top-50-albums-2012#slide-49|title=Guitar World's Top 50 Albums of 2012|work=Guitar World|date=2012-12-28|accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named "Stay Frosty" the 16th best song of 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-songs-of-2012-20121205/van-halen-stay-frosty-19691231|title=50 BEST SONGS OF 2012: 16 - Van Halen: Stay Frosty|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> and the magazine's readers put it as the fifth best album of the year.<ref>{{cite web|work=Rolling Stone|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/readers-poll-the-best-albums-of-2012-20121212/5-van-halen-a-different-kind-of-truth-0262926|title=Readers' Poll: The Best Albums of 2012 - 5. Van Halen, 'A Different Kind of Truth'|accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref>

===Commercial performance===
''A Different Kind of Truth'' entered the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at #2, selling 188,000 copies in its first six days of release. It is the group's fourteenth consecutive top ten album in the US.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Adele's '21' Hits 20th Week at No. 1, Van Halen Debuts at No. 2|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/news/adele-s-21-hits-20th-week-at-no-1-van-halen-1006195752.story|work=Billboard|accessdate=22 February 2012|date=15 February 2012}}</ref> By the end of 2012 the album had sold 411,000 copies in the US, making it the 72th best-selling record of the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peoples |first=Glenn |title=Business Matters: How Much Will Irving Azoff Be Missed on Live Nation's Bottom Line?||url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1510522/business-matters-how-much-will-irving-azoff-be-missed-on-live-nations|work=Billboard|accessdate=4 February 2012|date=January 02, 2013}}</ref><ref name=billend>http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/year-end/2012/the-billboard-200</ref>

The album also debuted at #6 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] with first-week sales of 14,040 copies, becoming their highest charting album ever.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Alan|title=Official Chart Analysis: Lana Del Rey scores biggest-selling album of 2012, Gotye shifts another 83k|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1048481|work=[[Music Week]]|accessdate=22 February 2012|date=13 February 2012}}</ref> In Japan, ''A Different Kind of Truth'' debuted at third on the [[Oricon]] chart, and was one of the very few albums by western artists to crack the year-end tally, finishing at number 89 with 79,517 copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Tom|title= Japan<U+2019>s Oricon Biggest Selling Singles and Album Chart 2012 Revealed|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/music/special/2012/musicrank1220/index08.html#topphoto}}</ref>

